<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">At the end of the Portage the bank is at least forty feet above the lake and is a mixture of sand gravel and Clay, the beach is covered with Round Whinstone or paving Stone<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Here you have again a full View of the blue expanse of water, rendered more pleasing from having em<span class="AddHand-author">er</span>ged from Surrounding hills and muddy Streams<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Coast now bends to the South for more than twenty leagues to the exception of three or four high and Rocky points which project northwesterly.  There are Several Rivers in this distance none of which <span class="DelHand-author">is</span> <span class="AddHand-author">are</span> remarkable until you arrive at the Natonagan which is fifteen leagues from the Portage and is larger &amp; deeper than any other we have hitherto Spoken of<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The beach at its entrance is low and Sandy but the banks Soon Rise Very high of a Stiff Red clay which tinges the water for quarter of a mile out and is the only exception to the black water of the Southern Rivers in a space of 140 leagues<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  A short distance from the enterance the River has a branch com<span class="DelHand-author">es</span><span class="AddHand-author">ing</span> from the South, but the main River descends from the South east and about five leagues up there is a mass of Copper ore in <span class="DelHand-author">the</span> its bed where the Indians go and cut off pieces</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[32]</span></p>

